liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) says it killed another Hamas commander on Wednesday in their second strike on the Jabalia refugee camp in two days. In a statement the military said its fighter jets had struck a Hamas command and control complex in Jabalia "based on precise intelligence", killing the head of the Islamist group's anti-tank missile unit, Muhammad A'sar. "Hamas deliberately builds its terror infrastructure under, around and within civilian buildings, intentionally endangering Gazan civilians," the statement said. There was no immediate word on possible casualties from the second explosion. It comes a day after Palestinian health officials said an Israeli air strike had killed about 50 people and injured 150 at Jabalia. Palestinians sifted through rubble in a desperate hunt for people trapped underneath after Wednesday's strike on the camp. "It is a massacre," one witness of the strike said. Israel has said Tuesday's strike on the same camp killed Ibrahim Biari, who it said was a ringleader of what it called the "murderous terror attack" on October 7. Reporting by Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel strikes refugee camp for a second time, says it killed Hamas militant

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ABC's Middle East correspondent Allyson Horn says 88 Australian citizens, permanent residents and their families have been stuck inside Gaza for more than three weeks "in what has been described as living hell". Today, for the first time since the Israel-Gaza war broke out, the Rafah border crossing was opened for foreign passport holders to leave. But Horn says some Australians are still stuck inside the seaside enclave: "The Australian authorities have confirmed to us that 23 people registered to them, including 20 Australians, have successfully now crossed over from Gaza into Egypt. "They say those people are now being assisted with onward travel, but, of course, that means that there are dozens of Australians who are still stuck inside Gaza. "I spoke with one man today who actually tried to go to the Rafah crossing today. He went there with his wife. He is an Australian passport holder. His wife has an Australian visa. "He said when he went to Rafah, because his wife didn't have an Australian passport, they were told that they were not allowed to cross." Horn says she also spoke to Australians who haven't even been able to make the journey to the Rafah crossing because it was too dangerous or they couldn't find any transport.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Dozens of Australians still stuck inside Gaza as Rafah border crossing opens

children.content: ABC's Middle East correspondent Allyson Horn says 88 Australian citizens, permanent residents and their families have been stuck inside Gaza for more than three weeks "in what has been described as living hell".
Today, for the first time since the Israel-Gaza war broke out, the Rafah border crossing was opened for foreign passport holders to leave.
But Horn says some Australians are still stuck inside the seaside enclave:
"The Australian authorities have confirmed to us that 23 people registered to them, including 20 Australians, have successfully now crossed over from Gaza into Egypt.
"They say those people are now being assisted with onward travel, but, of course, that means that there are
dozens of Australians who are still stuck inside Gaza.
"I spoke with one man today who actually tried to go to the Rafah crossing today. He went there with his wife. He is an Australian passport holder. His wife has an Australian visa.
"He said when he went to Rafah, because his wife
didn't have an Australian passport, they were told that they were not allowed to cross."
Horn says she also spoke to Australians who haven't even been able to make the journey to the Rafah crossing because it was too dangerous or they couldn't find any transport.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) says 20 Australian citizens and three other people registered with the government were able to leave Gaza. A woman clutching an Australian passport at the border said she was told by a relative that if she got to the Rafah crossing, she would be able to leave the enclave. "I carried all of my luggage and came here. It’s so crowded, there’s too many people, I can’t imagine how they’re suffering. I wish everyone can leave," she said. The woman said she and 14 members of her family were staying in one room in Gaza. "It’s very hard and dangerous to get food, you cannot imagine ... I had to push myself hard to get myself a piece of bread that I don’t even want to eat. It’s for the little ones. We have 17 kids in the family and there’s no food. [For] the past two days, there was no water. " She says she's relieved to be leaving, but fearful for the loved ones she has to leave behind. "I’m so glad that I’m going to see my family, but I’m not happy at all because I’m leaving my brothers and sisters and my whole family still here. I wish, inshallah, they will all be safe. The situation is terrible, very very bad and very sad as well."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australian woman who managed to leave Gaza says 'the situation is terrible'
